{
  "texts": [
    "Second, local jitter (different from neuron to neuron) has different effects than systematic time shifts for groups of neurons (e.g., a fixed delay in the response of a whole layer).",
    "Since frozen jitter is equivalent to (random) rescaling of parameters, it can be to a large degree compensated by fine-tuning with the hardware-in-the-loop using our method.",
    "Random jitter is in general more difficult to compensate than frozen jitter.",
    "Nevertheless, for local random jitter, Fig. 5a shows that fine-tuning with our training method leads to a significant improvement.",
    "We did not test random jitter that would affect a whole layer n with the same time shift (e.g., by randomly shifting the whole time interval ½t ðnÞ min, t ðnÞ max Þ between one trial and the next)."
  ]
}